original_poem:
amor é um fogo que arde sem se ver,
é ferida que doi, e não se sente;
é um contentamento descontente,
é dor que desatina sem doer.
é um não querer mais que bem querer;
é um andar solitário entre a gente;
é nunca contentar-se de contente;
é um cuidar que ganha em se perder.
é querer estar preso por vontade;
é servir a quem vence, o vencedor;
é ter com quem nos mata, lealdade.
mas como causar pode seu favor
nos corações humanos amizade,
se tão contrário a si é o mesmo amor?

translated_by_TA:
Love is a fire that burns without being seen,
It's a wound that hurts but isn't felt;
It's a discontented contentment,
It's a pain that raves without hurting.
It's not wanting more than to desire;
It's walking alone among the crowd;
It's never content with being content;
It's a concern that gains by being lost.
It's wanting to be imprisoned by choice;
It's serving the one who beats, the victor;
It's having loyalty to who kills us.
But how can its favor cause
Human hearts to feel friendship,
If love itself is so self-contradictory?

Because my eyes never tire of weeping
Sorrows that never tire of exhausting me;
For the fire in which I was kindled does not relent
By whom I could never soften;
Let blind love tire not of guiding me
To a place from which I know not how to return;
Nor let the whole world cease to hear me,
While my weak voice still has strength to remain.
And if in mountains, rivers, or valleys,
Pity dwells, or love resides within beasts, birds, plants, stones, waters,
Hear the long story of my woes
And heal their pain with my pain;
For great sorrows can heal sorrows.

Oh! how my weary pilgrimage grows,
year after year, more long and more slow!
how short my brief and vain human speech,
approaching its end, its course does reach!
my years are spent, and damage does grow;
a remedy I lose, which I did boast;
if by experience one does forecast,
any great hope is found to be a woe.
I run after this good that cannot be caught;
in the middle of the path, it's lost;
I fall a thousand times, and faith is smote.
when it escapes, I linger; and, in delay,
if I my eyes uplift to see if it's still in sight,
from vision and hope it's gone, out of sight.
